\begin_layout Standard
We have several choices.
 Listing these, with the pros and cons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Schwarzschild coordinates.
 Unacceptable, due ot the coordinate singularity at the (future) event horizon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Lemaître coordinates.
 Minor modification to Schwarzschild.
 Disadvantage: square roots and cube roots appear.
 Not geodesically complete.
 Advantage: the frame fields describe the a radially free-falling observer,
 falling from infinity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eddington–Finkelstein coordinates.
 These are a coordinate frame defined by radially infalling null geodesics.
 Advantage: the metric is independent of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Disadvantage: Not geodesically complete.
 Specifically, doesn't cover the past horizon (white-hole) part of the extended
 Schwarschild spacetime.
 But that's OK, because we're not interested in that part of the solution
 ...
 at the moment.
 Disadvantage: the constant-time hypersurfaces are null surfaces.
 I fear this will lead to confusion?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Gullstrand–Painlevé coordinates.
 Advantage: the metric is independent of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Another advantage: constant-time hypersurfaces are flat.
 The global time coordinate is the proper time of a radially free-falling
 observer.
 This seems like a good choice of coordinates, in part because these preserve
 some of the intuition we have about space.
 More abstractly, the space-like part of the tangent planes have a simple
 form.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Kruskal–Szekeres coordinates.
 Metric depends on both space and time, but is complete over the extended
 Schwarschild spacetime.
 Contains exponentials, sinh and cosh functions.
 Seems to be more complicated, both algebraically and numerically.
\end_layout

