\begin_layout Subsection*
Tangent vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fixing a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(t,r,\theta,\phi\right)$
\end_inset

 on the manifold, the past null tangent space is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $g=0$
\end_inset

; the timelike tangents are those with 
\begin_inset Formula $g=1$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, we are looking for vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}\left(\vec{v},\vec{v}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}\left(\vec{v},\vec{v}\right)=1$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=v_{t}\partial_{t}+v_{r}\partial_{r}+v_{\theta}\partial_{\theta}+v_{\phi}\partial_{\phi}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{g}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)dt\otimes dt-\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}\left(dt\otimes dr+dr\otimes dt\right)-dr\otimes dr-r^{2}\left(d\theta\otimes d\theta+\sin^{2}\theta\,d\phi\otimes d\phi\right)
\]

\end_inset

so obviously (duhh)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{g}\left(\vec{v},\vec{v}\right)=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)v_{t}^{2}-2\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}v_{t}v_{r}-v_{r}^{2}-r^{2}\left(v_{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\,v_{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Brute-forcing this by hand seems unpleasant, but I don't know of a better
 way just right now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first trick is to factor the above using the vielbein frames.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{g}\left(\vec{v},\vec{v}\right)=w_{0}^{2}-w_{1}^{2}-w_{2}^{2}-w_{3}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

with
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{0} & =v_{t}\\
w_{1} & =v_{r}+v_{t}\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}\\
w_{2} & =rv_{\theta}\\
w_{3} & =r\sin\theta\,v_{\phi}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Sometimes, we'll use the abbreviation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & \equiv\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{g}\left(\vec{v},\vec{v}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 is a one-sheeted hyperboliod outside of the EH, two-sheeted inside the
 EH.
 We can parametrize the hyperboloid with sinh and cosh, as is convetional.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets try some special cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Radial tangent vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Radial tangents will have 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\theta}=v_{\phi}=0$
\end_inset

 (and so 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{2}=w_{3}=0)$
\end_inset

 and the null tangents solve 
\begin_inset Formula $0=w_{0}^{2}-w_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}=\pm w_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Fixing 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}=\pm\left(v_{r}+Sv_{t}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for the radial null tangents.
 The time-like tangents solve 
\begin_inset Formula $1=w_{0}^{2}-w_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}=\pm\sqrt{1+w_{1}^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging through gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{t}=\frac{Sv_{r}\pm\sqrt{v_{r}^{2}+1-S^{2}}}{1-S^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

(if I did things correctly.) Quite unenlightening.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The correct solution is to start the massive particle at rest, and infinity.
 That is, at 
\begin_inset Formula $r\to\infty$
\end_inset

, one sets 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}=1$
\end_inset

.
 The correspons to 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Radial infall is then done by holding 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 all the way in.
 The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 measures the proper time on this geodesic, and we get points on it by solving
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 I'm hand-waving a bit here; solving for the radially-infalling geodesic
 is standard homework problem, and assorted class-note PDF's online show
 exactly how to do this.
 I'm not going to repeat just right now.
 But more or less, they go like this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\int dt=\int\frac{dt}{dr}dr=\int\frac{dr}{v_{r}}=-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2m}}\int\sqrt{r}dr=-\frac{2}{3}\frac{r^{3/2}}{\sqrt{2m}}
\]

\end_inset

and then plug in the integration limits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Geodesic Equations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest approach to the geodesics seems to be the Lagrangian approach;
 which we mimic from the earlier Part Three of this diary.
 The nicest thing about it is that it gives us a constant of motion, for
 free.
 We've also already done the work in one coord system; we just repeat the
 genral logic in another.
 Should be easy, right?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}g_{\mu\nu}\dot{x}^{\mu}\dot{x}^{\nu}
\]

\end_inset

where the shorthand 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}^{\mu}=\frac{dx^{\mu}}{d\tau}
\]

\end_inset

is used.
 It's also handy to recall the Legendre transform.
 Defining the conjugate momentum as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{\mu}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}
\]

\end_inset

the Hamiltonian is then 
\begin_inset Formula $H=p_{\mu}\dot{x}^{\mu}-L$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Gullstrand–Painlevé chart, it is as always a cut-n-paste job
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}^{2}-2\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}\dot{t}\dot{r}-\dot{r}^{2}-r^{2}\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

The Euler-Lagrange equations are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{x}^{\mu}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial x^{\mu}}=0
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=t$
\end_inset

 one obviously has 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial L/\partial t=0$
\end_inset

 and so one has a constant of motion:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}
\]

\end_inset

Call this the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Working this out explicitly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{const}=\frac{E}{m}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{t}}=\left(1-\frac{2m}{r}\right)\dot{t}-\sqrt{\frac{2m}{r}}\dot{r}
\]

\end_inset

This is written so that the constant is dimensionless, and the energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has the same units as the mass.
 For null geodesics, one has a conformal time; just use 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and ignore the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 The above can be rwritten in the beguiling form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Sw_{1}=\dot{t}-\frac{E}{m}
\]

\end_inset

This allows a remarkable (and confusing) calculation (did I make a mistake??)
 Since the RHS is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, the partial vanishes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=S\frac{\partial w_{1}}{\partial r}+w_{1}\frac{\partial S}{\partial r}
\]

\end_inset

Then, plugging in
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial S}{\partial r} & =-\frac{S}{2r}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

results in
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial w_{1}}{\partial r}=\frac{w_{1}}{2r}
\]

\end_inset

which is wacky and wild, since explicit differention gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial w_{1}}{\partial r}=\dot{t}\frac{\partial S}{\partial r}=-\frac{\dot{t}S}{2r}
\]

\end_inset

Equating these two gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\dot{r}+2S\dot{t}
\]

\end_inset

which is surprising.
 We have to be careful: this would only hold on surfaces of constant energy?!
 Unexpected but plausible, I guess.
 I'm confused and suspicious.
 Something seems wrong, but I can't see the mistake.
 Plugging this around gives 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=-S\dot{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{w_{1}}=-S\ddot{t}-\dot{t}\dot{S}=-S\ddot{t}+S\dot{t}\dot{r}/2r$
\end_inset

 and so Hmmm.
 I'm floundering, I'm missing something, here.
 I beleive that there's some elegant way to talk about this, but I don't
 know what it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Radial eqns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\mu}=r$
\end_inset

, the radial equation is brute-forced:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{m}{r^{2}}\dot{t}^{2}+\frac{1}{2r}S\dot{t}\dot{r}-r\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Plugging in the energy simplifies this slightly, to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=\frac{\dot{t}}{2r}\left(1-\frac{E}{m}\right)-r\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

And I guess other forms are possible ...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The momentum is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{r}=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}=-\left(\dot{r}+S\dot{t}\right)=-w_{1}
\]

\end_inset

Brute force gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}= & -S\ddot{t}-\dot{t}\frac{dS}{d\tau}-\ddot{r}\\
= & -S\ddot{t}+\dot{t}\dot{r}\frac{S}{2r}-\ddot{r}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

but we can also differentiate the energy condition to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{t}=\dot{S}w_{1}+S\dot{w_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and use 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{S}=-S\dot{r}/2r$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{w_{1}}=\frac{\ddot{t}}{S}+\frac{\dot{r}}{2r}w_{1}
\]

\end_inset

which is clearly simpler.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining these simpler forms gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{r}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial r}=-\frac{\ddot{t}}{S}-\frac{\dot{r}}{2r}w_{1}-\frac{\dot{t}}{2r}\left(1-\frac{E}{m}\right)+r\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

We can certainly try to integrate this numerically, but no easy by-hand
 work seems to pop up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Perhaps we should work with 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}$
\end_inset

 directly, so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=-\dot{w_{1}}-\frac{\dot{t}}{2r}\left(1-\frac{E}{m}\right)+r\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which looks simpler.
 Then using one of the crazy identities above, of 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=-S\dot{t}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=-\dot{w_{1}}+\frac{w_{1}}{2rS}\left(1-\frac{E}{m}\right)+r\left(\dot{\theta}^{2}+\sin^{2}\theta\dot{\phi}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is a first-order eqn.
 This looks tractable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anyway, we should double-check this to make sure we did not miss some easier,
