\begin_layout Subsection*
Angular eqns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although it's tedious, we should do the same for the angular coords.
 Below, we brute-force it; but we should really employ the angular momentum
 as a constant of motion.
 So, for example,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\phi}=0
\]

\end_inset

and thus we deduce 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{\phi}}=-2r\sin^{2}\theta\,\dot{\phi}=-2J=\mbox{const}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 the angular momentum.
 Differentiating explcitly, we get, up to a constant
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\dot{J}=\sin^{2}\theta\left(\ddot{\phi}\,r+\dot{r}\dot{\phi}+2\dot{\phi}\dot{\theta}r\frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The other coordinate gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\theta}= & -2r\sin\theta\cos\theta\,\dot{\phi^{2}}\\
= & -\frac{2\cos\theta}{r\sin\theta}J^{2}\\
\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{\theta}}= & -2r\dot{\theta}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{\partial L}{\partial\dot{\theta}}-\frac{\partial L}{\partial\theta}=r^{2}\ddot{\theta}+r\dot{r}\dot{\theta}-\frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}J^{2}
\]

\end_inset

and Bleh.
 The correct approach is probably to just transform to cordinates in which
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi/2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}=0$
\end_inset

, solve for constant angular momentum, which becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $J=r\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 and then rotate back to wherever we needed to be.
 Yuck.
\end_layout

